# Waikouaiti County Council Reserve Vesting Act 1910Local Act1910 No 13

Date of assent21 November 1910

## Contents

[Title][0]
    
*   [Preamble][1]

[1][2] [Short Title][2]

[2][3] [Vesting of land as endowment for county][3]

[Schedule][4]  
[][4]

---

An Act to vest a certain Reserve, known as the Waikouaiti Steep Hill Recreation and Commonage Reserve, in the Corporation of the County of Waikouaiti as an Endowment Reserve.
    
*   #### Preamble
    
    WHEREAS the parcel of land described in the Schedule hereto was vested in the Waikouaiti Road Board in trust as a reserve for recreation and commonage, for the use of the inhabitants of Waikouaiti: And whereas by a special order of the Waikouaiti County Council, dated the thirtieth day of June, eighteen hundred and eighty-two, the said Waikouaiti Road District was merged in the Waikouaiti County: And whereas it is expedient that the said parcel of land should be vested in the Corporation of the said County Waikouaiti for the purposes hereinafter mentioned:

BE IT THEREFORE ENACTED by the General Assembly of New Zealand in Parliament assembled, and by the authority of the same, as follows:---

##### 1 Short Title
    
*   This Act may be cited as the Waikouaiti County Council Reserve Vesting Act 1910\.

##### 2 Vesting of land as endowment for county
    
*   The parcel of land described in the Schedule to this Act is hereby vested in the Corporation of the Chairman, Councillors, and Inhabitants of the County of Waikouaiti as an endowment for the benefit of the said county.

---

## Schedule

ALL that parcel of land in the Otago Land District, containing by admeasurement 1,131 acres 32 poles, more or less, being a commonage reserve in Blocks VIII and IX, Waikouaiti Survey District: bounded towards the north-east by Section 9 and a road-line for a distance of 2602 links; towards the north-west by said road-line for a distance of 10750 links; towards the east by Sections 41, 85, a road-line, Sections 91, 90, and 40, Block II, by two road-lines and part of Section 1, Block I, aforesaid survey district, for a distance of 11500 links; towards the south by Section 1, Block VIII, for a distance of 3199 links; towards the west by part of Section 7, and by Section 8, for a distance of 4416 links; again towards the south by Sections 8, 5, and a road-line for a distance of 4690 links; again towards to east by said Section 5 for a distance of 1690 links; towards the north by part of said Section 5 for a distance of 2813 links; towards the south-east by a road-line for a distance of 1152 links; again towards the east by Section 7 for a distance of 3338 links; again towards the north by said Section 7 and a road-line for a distance of 2307 links; again towards the east by Section 1 and Crown Lands Block IX for a distance of 3400 links; again towards the north by said Crown lands for a distance of 3199 links; again towards the east by part of Section 18 and a road-line, Block I, for a distance of 1580 links; again towards the south by Section 4, four road-lines, and a mining reserve, Block IX, for a distance of 7500 links; and again towards the west and south-west generally by the Waikouaiti River (south branch) for a distance of 6650 links and 26300 links, and intersected by five road-lines: be all the aforesaid linkages more or less: as the same is delineated on the plan deposited in the office of the Chief Surveyor, in Dunedin.

